ce:section.ce:para:
Photocatalysis has huge potential in utilization of sunlight for eliminating toxic environmental pollutants and synthesizing valuable chemicals and fuels [1–3], because it has the distinguished advantages of lower cost and more environmental benefits as compared with other traditional technologies. For the practical applications of photocatalytic technology, highly efficient visible-light photocatalysts are desired. As a low cost, harmless, stable, CdI2-type layered semiconductor material (Eg = 2.0–2.3 eV [4–11]), SnS2 is promising for use as a visible-light photocatalyst. So far, SnS2 has been researched for many photocatalytic applications, including the reduction of Cr(VI) [4,5] and CO2 [6,7], production of H2 from H2O [8,9], and degradation of azo dyes [10,11]. Nevertheless, SnS2 has the same major drawback as most other semiconductor photocatalysts: the photoinduced electrons (e−
                     ) and holes (h+
                     ) are apt to recombine at a high rate, leading to unsatisfactory photocatalytic activity. Therefore, it is both necessary and meaningful to explore applicable modification methods for improving the photocatalytic activity of SnS2 [12–19].
